ARTICLE I. - IN GENERAL 

Secs. 50-1—50-30. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE II. - POLICE DEPARTMENT[2] 

Footnotes: 
--- (2) --- 
Cross reference— Administration, ch. 2.

Sec. 50-31. - Duties. 
The county police department and its duly appointed personnel shall, under the direction and control of the board of commissioners, have the following duties and powers: 
(1)	Maintain the peace, good order and tranquility of the county by arresting and prosecuting those persons violating any county ordinances or resolutions, or any state or federal law; 
(2)	Enforce all county regulations;
(3)	Protect the rights of persons and property of the county;
(4)	Guard and protect the public health of the county;
(5)	Issue citations for violations of any county ordinances, resolutions or regulations for the prompt prosecution of any such violators in the county magistrate court; 
(6)	Issue a report in writing each month to the board of commissioners reflecting the number and type of citations issued, the disposition of such citations, and such other documentation as the board of commissioners may request; 
(7)	Make arrests and execute and return criminal warrants and processes in the county just as the sheriff of the county is authorized to do; 
(8)	Such other powers in the county as held by the sheriff of such county as a peace officer; and 
(9)	Such other duties as may be required of him under this article or in any county ordinance, resolution or regulation, or by the board of commissioners. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 1)
Sec. 50-32. - Qualifications. 
All personnel of the county police department shall satisfy the following minimum requirements prior to being hired: 
(1)	Be at least 18 years of age;
(2)	Be a citizen of the United States;
(3)	Have a high school diploma or its recognized equivalent;
(4)	Not have been convicted by any state or by the federal government of any crime the punishment for which could have been imprisonment in the federal or state prison or institution nor have been convicted of sufficient misdemeanors to establish a pattern of disregard for the law, provided that, for purposes of this subsection, violations of traffic laws and other offenses involving the operation of motor vehicles when the applicant has received a pardon shall not be considered; 
(5)	Be fingerprinted and a search made of local, state and national fingerprint files to disclose any criminal record; 
(6)	Possess good moral character as determined by an investigation under procedure established by the state peace officer standards and training council; 
(7)	Have an oral interview with the board of commissioners or its representative to determine the applicant's appearance, background and ability to communicate; 
(8)	Be found, after examination by a licensed physician or surgeon, to be free from any physical, emotional or mental conditions which might adversely affect his exercising the powers or duties of a peace officer; 
(9)	Successfully complete a job related academy entrance examination provided for and administered by the state peace officer standards and training council in conformity with state and federal law; 
(10)	Shall satisfactorily complete a basic training course within 12 months of his appointment as provided for in O.C.G.A. § 35-8-9, with such course being taken at any school certified by the state peace officer standards and training council; and 
(11)	Be approved for appointment by a majority vote of the board of commissioners.
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 2)
Sec. 50-33. - Number of officers appointed; terms of office; removal. 
(a)	The board of commissioners shall, in its sole discretion, determine the number of police officers to be employed by the county and to serve its police department. 
(b)	Such officers shall be appointed by a majority vote of the board of commissioners, and each officer shall serve at the pleasure of the board of commissioners with any such officer being subject to being removed from office at any time, at the will of the board of commissioners, with or without cause. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 3)
Sec. 50-34. - Bond. 
Each officer appointed to serve on the county police department shall enter into a good and solvent bond, in a sum of not less than $1,000.00, or such other sum as the board of commissioners may fix, conditioned for the faithful performance of all his official duties. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 4)
Sec. 50-35. - Salaries. 
(a)	The board of commissioners shall fix the salaries of those appointed to serve on the county police department, and such salaries, together with the expense of maintaining the police department, shall be paid out of the county treasury. 
(b)	The board of commissioners is authorized to levy such tax as may be necessary to pay such salaries and expenses over and above the sums for which it is otherwise authorized to levy a tax. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 5)
Sec. 50-36. - Chief of police; designation; scope of authority. 
In its sole discretion, the board of commissioners may designate an officer of the county police department to serve as its chief, who shall serve under the direction and control of the board of commissioners. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 6)
Sec. 50-37. - Promulgation of rules and regulations. 
The board of commissioners shall have the authority to promulgate and make rules and regulations for the conduct, management and control of the county police department and its officers, and it shall, in its discretion, be empowered to enlarge, modify or change such rules and regulations. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1989, § 7)

