ARTICLE I. - IN GENERAL 

Secs. 58-1—58-30. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE II. - SMOKING IN COUNTY BUILDINGS AND VEHICLES[2] 

Footnotes: 
--- (2) --- 
Cross reference— Health and sanitation, ch. 46.

Sec. 58-31. - Definitions. 
The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: 
County building means any building or structure located on real estate that the county owns, leases or has under its control. 
County vehicle means any motorized vehicle to which the county holds title, ownership, leases or borrows for county governmental purposes. 
Tobacco products means any product produced from the plant called tobacco or the family of plants from the genus Nicotiana. These products shall include, but not be limited to, pipe tobacco, smoking tobacco, cigars, cigarettes, cigarillos, chewing tobacco, snuff or smokeless tobacco. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1995, app. IV, § 4.1)
Cross reference— Definitions generally, § 1-2. 
Sec. 58-32. - Prohibited acts. 
(a)	It shall be unlawful for any person to smoke or use any tobacco products in any county building or any building under the care and control of the county. 
(b)	It shall be unlawful for any person to smoke or to use any tobacco product in a county vehicle. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1995, art. V, § 5.0)
Sec. 58-33. - Penalty for violation of article. 
(a)	Any person violating this article, other than a county employee, will be asked to stop the use of tobacco products or to leave the county building or vehicle. Any person who refuses to stop using tobacco products while in a county building or a county vehicle will be escorted from the property or removed from the vehicle by an officer of the county sheriff's department. 
(b)	Any county employee violating this article will be punished as provided in the county civil service personnel policy. 
(Ord. of 7-3-1995, art. VI)
Secs. 58-34—58-65. - Reserved. 
ARTICLE III. - DISORDERLY CONDUCT 

Sec. 58-66. - Defined; declared unlawful. 
Those acts described in section 58-67 shall be deemed disorderly conduct, and it shall be unlawful for any person to do or engage in any of such acts. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1993, § 2(2.1))
Sec. 58-67. - Specific acts enumerated. 
The following acts shall be defined as disorderly conduct in violation of this article: 
(1)	Act in a violent or tumultuous manner toward another, whereby any person is placed in danger of or in fear of his safety, life, limb or health; 
(2)	Act in a violent or tumultuous manner toward another, whereby public property or property of another person is placed in danger of being destroyed or damaged; 
(3)	Endanger or interfere with the lawful pursuits of another by acts of violence or threats of bodily harm; 
(4)	Cause, provoke or engage in any fight, brawl or riotous conduct so as to endanger the life, limb, health or property of another or public property; 
(5)	Assemble or congregate with another or others and cause, provoke or engage in any fight or brawl; 
(6)	Collect in bodies or in crowds and engage in unlawful activities;
(7)	Assemble or congregate with another or others and engage or attempt to engage in gambling;
(8)	Frequent any public place and obtain money from another by an illegal and fraudulent scheme, trick, artifice or device or attempt to do so; 
(9)	Assemble with another or others and engage in any fraudulent scheme, device or trick to obtain or attempt to obtain any valuable thing in any place or from any person; 
(10)	Utter, in a public place or any place open to the public, any obscene words or epithets;
(11)	Frequent any place or vehicle where gambling or the illegal sale or possession of alcoholic beverages or narcotics or dangerous drugs is practiced, allowed or tolerated; 
(12)	Use fighting words directed towards any person, causing such person to become outraged and thus create turmoil; 
(13)	Assemble or congregate with another or others and do bodily harm to another or property of another or public property; 
(14)	Interfere with another's pursuit of a lawful occupation by acts of violence or threats thereof; 
(15)	Congregate with another or others in or on any public way so as to halt the flow of vehicular or pedestrian traffic and to refuse to clear such public way when ordered to do so by a peace officer or other person having authority; 
(16)	Damage, befoul or disturb public property or the property of another so as to create a hazardous, unhealthy or physically offensive condition; 
(17)	Appear in public in an intoxicated state or condition, whether such intoxication is by alcohol or drugs; 
(18)	Expose any part of one's body in an indecent or rude manner;
(19)	Create loud noises which disrupt, disturb or otherwise interfere with the peace and tranquility of the public; 
(20)	Attempt to hinder, delay, obstruct or prevent any law enforcement officer from performing his duty; 
(21)	Keep a disorderly house or house of ill fame and all adults residing in the house shall be considered a keeper; 
(22)	Linger or loiter along public sidewalks, streets or public ways of the county;
(23)	Fail or refuse to remove himself from the private property of another when requested to do so by the owner or occupants thereof; and 
(24)	Alone or in concert with others, with the intent of appropriating merchandise to his own use without paying for the same or to deprive the owner of possession thereof or the value thereof, in whole or in part, by concealing or taking possession of the goods or merchandise from a retail establishment, or to alter the price tag or other price marking of goods or merchandise of any store or retail establishment, wrongfully causing the amount paid to be less than the merchant's stated price for the merchandise of property or value thereof of $100.00 or less; 
(25)	Jumping, diving, or otherwise propelling one's self from a public bridge; fishing from a public bridge; and assembling or congregating on a public bridge in such a manner as to impede the flow of traffic. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1993, § 2(2.2))
Sec. 58-68. - Continued conduct. 
Continuation of the disorderly conduct constitutes additional offenses. Each day that the disorderly conduct continues shall constitute a new and separate offense and the judge of the county magistrate court may impose such sentence as the circumstances may require. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1993, § 2(art. III))
Sec. 58-69. - Penalty for violation of article. 
Any person who pleads guilty, nolo contendere or is convicted of violating the provisions of this article, shall be punished as provided in O.C.G.A. § 36-1-20 or such other general law as may be in the future enacted to provide for punishment and penalties that may be imposed by the magistrate courts of the state. As provided in O.C.G.A. § 36-1-20, each violation of this article may be punished as provided in section 1-19. In addition to the fine or jail sentence, the judge may impose community service. 
(Ord. of 1-4-1993, § 2(art. IV))
Chapters 59—61 - RESERVED
